Verifiers are crucial components for enhancing modern LLMs’ reasoning capability. Typical verifiers require resource-intensive supervised dataset construction, which is costly and faces limitations in data diversity. In this paper, we propose L O V ER , an unsupervised verifier regularized by logical rules. L O V ER treats the verifier as a binary latent variable, utilizing internal activations and enforcing three logical constraints on multiple reasoning paths: negation consistency, intra-group consistency, and inter-group consistency (grouped by the final answer). By incorporating logical rules as priors, L O V ER can leverage unlabeled examples and is directly compatible with any off-the-shelf LLMs. Experiments on 10 datasets demonstrate that L O V ER significantly outperforms unsupervised baselines, achieving performance comparable to the supervised verifier (reaching its 95% level on average). The source code is publicly available at https://github.com/ wangxinyufighting/llm-lover.